The death toll from Covid-19 hit 1,552 after seven more patients died on Wednesday. Health CS Mutahi Kagwe said in a statement that 561 Kenyans had tested positive for the virus, raising the caseload in the country to 89,661. Some 6,387 samples were tested in 24 hours, representing a positivity rate of 8.7 per cent. “We seem to be on a gradual decline and we hope that we will be able to maintain this. The only challenge that we may face is that we are getting into the festive season and this is a time when the spread of the virus can be accelerated,” Health CAS Rashid Aman said. There were 22 foreigners among the cases. The men were 387 and women 174. “There are 1,096 patients admitted in various health facilities countrywide with 8,016 are on the home-based isolation and care. Sixty-three patients are in the intensive care unit, 32 of whom are on ventilator support and 26 on supplemental oxygen,” Kagwe said. According to the CS, five patients are on observation. “Another 71 patients are separately on supplemental oxygen out of whom 63 are in the general wards while eight are in the high dependency unit,” he added. Similarly, 355 patients recovered from the disease, raising the number of recoveries to 70,174. From the number, 274 were from the home-based care programme while 81 were discharged from various hospitals. Nairobi registered 189 more cases, followed by Mombasa with 85, Bungoma with 65, Busia with 36, Kericho, Kiambu and Kwale with 19 new cases each and Kisumu with 17 cases. Other counties include Embu with 13, Kilifi with 12, Nakuru and Lamu with 11 cases each, Uasin Gishu and Marsabit with nine cases each, Kakamega with seven, Nyeri and Kirinyaga with six, Machakos and Laikipia with four and Kajiado with three. Murang’a, Homa Bay, Turkana, Makueni and Tana River recorded two cases each while Taita Taveta, Nyandarua, Elgeyo Marakwet, Vihiga, meru, Siaya and Trans Nzoia had one case each. 